Add @water{240%ml} and the @chicken stock{1%sachet} to a large #pot{} for the 
@bulgur wheat{120%g}.

Chop the @sweet potato{1}(chopped into 2cm chunks, peeling optional).

Drain and rinse the @lentils{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Zest and quarter the @lime{1}. Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}.

Stir the @coconut milk{1%pack} (or shake the packet) to dissolve any lumps.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Once the water is boiling, stir in the bulgur then bring back to the boil.

Simmer for ~{1%minute} then pop a #lid{} on the pot and remove from the heat.

Leave aside for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Just before serving, stir the lime zest through the bulgur, fluffing it up as 
you go.

Meanwhile, place a large pan over high heat with a generous drizzle of 
@oil{to taste}.

When hot, add the @diced Irish chicken breast{260%g} and sweet potato and 
cook until browned on the outside, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal 
due to packaging used to keep it fresh.

Lower the heat of the pan to medium-high then add the @ras-el-hanout{1%sachet} 
with a pinch of @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @chopped tomatoes with onion & garlic{1%pack}, coconut milk, 
@water{75%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} into the pan.

> Double the water and sugar amounts for 4p.

Stir in the lentils and @peanut butter{1%sachet} and give everything a good mix.

Bring to the boil, cover and simmer until the chicken is cooked through, 
~{10-12%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if the stew becomes too thick.

Spoon the fluffy bulgur into #bowls{}.

Top with generous helpings of chicken, lentil and sweet potato stew.

Garnish with scallion, @peanuts{20%g} and lime wedges.